{{- define "coder_integration_fix" -}}

=== INTEGRATION FIX MODE ===
This task previously failed to merge into the integration branch.
Your PRIMARY objective is to resolve the merge conflict and ensure the implementation still works.

CRITICAL UNDERSTANDING - How Rebase Solves Commit History Issues:
- Git automatically SKIPS commits that already exist in integration (same commit SHA)
- After rebasing onto integration, your branch will contain ONLY commits unique to your task
- Example: If your branch has [A, B, C] and integration already has [A, B], rebase leaves only [C]
- Verify this with: git log --oneline {{.Config.IntegrationBranch}}..HEAD (shows commits unique to your branch)
- If you see the wrong number of commits after rebase, your commits have different SHAs than integration

INTEGRATION FIX WORKFLOW:

1. ASSESS THE CONFLICT
   cd {{.WorktreePath}}
   git status
   # Review conflicted files and understand what changed on integration branch

2. UPDATE LOCAL BRANCH
   git fetch {{.Config.ProjectRoot}} {{.Config.IntegrationBranch}}
   # Note: This is a local-only repository, so we fetch from project root, not 'origin'

3. REBASE ONTO INTEGRATION BRANCH
   git rebase {{.Config.IntegrationBranch}}
   # Git will pause at conflicts. Proceed to step 4.
   # Git automatically skips commits that already exist in integration (same SHA)

3.5. VERIFY COMMIT HISTORY
   # After rebase completes successfully, verify your branch state:
   git log --oneline {{.Config.IntegrationBranch}}..HEAD

   Expected result: Should show ONLY commits unique to your task
   - If you see commits that should be in integration already, continue to step 3.6
   - If commit count looks correct, skip to step 4

3.6. IF AUTO-SKIP DIDN'T WORK (Different SHAs)
   # This means they're different commit objects with similar content
   # Use interactive rebase to manually drop out-of-scope commits:
   git rebase -i {{.Config.IntegrationBranch}}

   # In the editor:
   #   - Mark out-of-scope commits as "drop" (commits already in integration)
   #   - Keep only your task's commits as "pick"
   git log --oneline {{.Config.IntegrationBranch}}..HEAD  # Verify again

4. RESOLVE CONFLICTS
   # For each conflicted file:
   #   a. Open the file and resolve conflict markers (<<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>>)
   #   b. Ensure the merged code preserves both your changes and integration branch changes
   #   c. Mark resolved: git add <file>
   # After all conflicts resolved:
   git rebase --continue

5. IF CONFLICTS ARE UNRESOLVABLE OR HISTORY IS CORRUPTED

   Option A: Mark as blocked if design conflict
   # If you cannot resolve conflicts without breaking the implementation:
   git rebase --abort
   # Use liza_mark_blocked tool with parameters:
   {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}", "agent_id": "{{.Config.AgentID}}", "reason": "Merge conflicts cannot be resolved without redesigning: <explain>", "questions": ["What is the intended behavior when...", "Should we..."]}

   Option B: Start completely fresh if commit history is wrong
   # If commit history is corrupted and can't be fixed with interactive rebase:
   git diff HEAD > /tmp/my-changes.patch
   # Delete and recreate worktree using MCP tools:
   # Use liza_wt_delete tool with parameters:
   {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}"}
   # Use liza_wt_create tool with parameters (creates from integration branch automatically):
   {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}"}
   cd {{.WorktreePath}}
   git apply /tmp/my-changes.patch

6. VALIDATE IMPLEMENTATION
   # After successful rebase:
   #   - Run all tests to ensure they still pass
   #   - Verify all done_when criteria still met
   #   - Check that your changes work with integration branch updates

7. SUBMIT FOR REVIEW (SAME AS NORMAL)
   # Once conflicts resolved and tests passing:
   # Get commit: git -C {{.WorktreePath}} rev-parse HEAD
   # Use liza_submit_for_review tool with: {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}", "commit_sha": "...", "agent_id": "{{.Config.AgentID}}"}

CRITICAL: Do not skip the rebase step. Merge conflicts mean the integration branch has diverged.
Simply re-running tests without rebasing will not fix the integration failure.

{{- end -}}
